274
00:15:42,567 --> 00:15:44,082
Well, I...

275
00:15:45,631 --> 00:15:48,448
Maybe I haven't done my best.

276
00:15:50,748 --> 00:15:53,306
I guess I owe that to the old man, don't I?

277
00:15:55,241 --> 00:15:56,251
Well, ah...

278
00:15:58,134 --> 00:16:00,417
Thanks for the chat, Niles. You're a good brother,

279
00:16:00,418 --> 00:16:02,770
and a credit to the psychiatric profession.

280
00:16:03,120 --> 00:16:04,572
You're a good brother too.

281
00:16:11,441 --> 00:16:12,550
Daphne?

282
00:16:13,725 --> 00:16:15,277
What are my things doing here?

283
00:16:15,278 --> 00:16:17,417
My leather wing chair? My Kusami lamp?

284
00:16:17,418 --> 00:16:19,847
We're putting them in the storage room, in the basement.

285
00:16:20,184 --> 00:16:23,568
There was no room for them in the study once we got my furniture in.

286
00:16:23,569 --> 00:16:25,688
We discussed it last night, remember?

287
00:16:25,689 --> 00:16:26,684
Of course, of course.

288
00:16:27,045 --> 00:16:30,723
I was just on my way to ask that peculiar little man from building services

289
00:16:30,724 --> 00:16:32,367
to give me a hand moving them.

290
00:16:32,368 --> 00:16:34,562
Oh, yes, Kyle. Well, give him my regards.

291
00:16:34,563 --> 00:16:36,646
Oh yeah, Remind me again

292
00:16:36,961 --> 00:16:39,547
which one of Kyle's eyes is really looking at me?

293
00:16:41,944 --> 00:16:42,962
The brown one.

294
00:16:54,508 --> 00:16:56,648
Daphne left your dinner in the fridge, if you're hungry.

295
00:16:56,649 --> 00:16:58,283
Well thanks, but I'm not.

296
00:16:58,284 --> 00:17:05,290
Ah... Dad, I'm sorry about the blow-up earlier.

297
00:17:05,291 --> 00:17:07,473
Ah, forget about it. I already have.

298
00:17:07,763 --> 00:17:11,120
You know, I guess there's no secret that these's been a lot of tension between us,

299
00:17:11,121 --> 00:17:14,565
and I think maybe one of the reasons is that we never have a chance to sit down and talk.

300
00:17:14,566 --> 00:17:19,036
And I... I thought we might have a conversation.

301
00:17:19,037 --> 00:17:19,927
Right now?

302
00:17:20,822 --> 00:17:22,763
Yes, I think now would be a good time.

303
00:17:23,058 --> 00:17:24,356
Later would be better.

304
00:17:26,006 --> 00:17:27,710
It doesn't have to be a long, drawn-out conversation,

305
00:17:27,711 --> 00:17:29,780
I'm talking about three minutes of you life.

306
00:17:29,781 --> 00:17:31,585
Well, I hope it is only three minutes,

307
00:17:31,586 --> 00:17:32,962
'cause my program's coming on.

308
00:17:32,963 --> 00:17:33,749
Well, alright.

309
00:17:33,750 --> 00:17:38,314
If it'll make you any happier I will get the egg-timer and I will set it for three minutes.

310
00:17:40,530 --> 00:17:41,859
So, what do you want to talk about?

311
00:17:42,382 --> 00:17:46,587
Well, the idea is for us to have a normal, honest conversation

312
00:17:46,588 --> 00:17:49,344
just like two normal people without getting on each other's nerves.

313
00:17:52,449 --> 00:17:57,880
Ready? Go

314
00:17:58,568 --> 00:17:59,754
This is stupid.

315
00:18:00,378 --> 00:18:02,790
One second? That's our personal best?

316
00:18:07,453 --> 00:18:10,535
Let us see if we can beat it.

317
00:18:12,327 --> 00:18:14,787
Ready? Go

318
00:18:17,802 --> 00:18:20,071
So how about those Seahawks?

319
00:18:20,072 --> 00:18:21,102
No sports.

320
00:18:21,103 --> 00:18:22,692
- All right. No opera.
- Agreed.

321
00:18:26,890 --> 00:18:30,027
Ready? Go

322
00:18:33,455 --> 00:18:35,684
This is your idea, you say something first.

323
00:18:37,295 --> 00:18:39,745
Alright, alright. I'll, I'll tell you something about myself,

324
00:18:39,746 --> 00:18:41,825
that, ah, that you don't know.

325
00:18:42,937 --> 00:18:44,059
Ah, six months ago,

326
00:18:44,060 --> 00:18:49,055
when Lilith and I were really on the rocks, ah,

327
00:18:49,832 --> 00:18:53,284
there was a time of depression I went through that was so terrible

328
00:18:53,285 --> 00:18:59,971
I actually climbed out on a ledge and wondered if life was worth living. I...

329
00:19:00,756 --> 00:19:04,033
And then I thought of Frederick.

330
00:19:04,732 --> 00:19:06,322
And you didn't jump, huh?

331
00:19:13,072 --> 00:19:14,197
Good, dad.

332
00:19:15,694 --> 00:19:17,557
Wow. I never knew that.

333
00:19:17,558 --> 00:19:19,817
Well, that's the point of this whole experiment.

334
00:19:19,818 --> 00:19:23,297
To tell one another something that we don't know about each other.

335
00:19:23,728 --> 00:19:26,232
Something vulnerable. Now it's your turn.

336
00:19:27,208 --> 00:19:28,253
Okay.

337
00:19:29,840 --> 00:19:31,904
Well, about two months ago,

338
00:19:32,395 --> 00:19:35,590
I was in the basement, going through some old pictures of your mother and me...

339
00:19:36,205 --> 00:19:38,373
and all of the sudden something flew up in my eye.

340
00:19:39,155 --> 00:19:41,738
And, when I was trying to get it out,

341
00:19:41,739 --> 00:19:46,065
I realised I could turn my eyelid inside out, the way kids do at camp.

342
00:19:48,285 --> 00:19:50,892
That's it? You call that vulnerable?

343
00:19:50,893 --> 00:19:51,815
It hurt.

344
00:19:51,816 --> 00:19:52,816
Oh well...

345
00:19:53,229 --> 00:19:55,237
I'm not talking about that kind of pain,

346
00:19:55,238 --> 00:19:58,185
I'm talking about your emotions, your soul.

347
00:19:58,482 --> 00:20:01,711
Some sort of painful, gut- wrenching experience.

348
00:20:01,712 --> 00:20:02,671
Other than this one?

349
00:20:02,672 --> 00:20:04,599
Oh, God! Always the flip answer.

350
00:20:05,351 --> 00:20:06,899
Well, this whole thing's stupid.

351
00:20:06,900 --> 00:20:08,054
Well, not to me.

352
00:20:08,055 --> 00:20:09,813
Oh, how should I expect anything out of you?

353
00:20:09,814 --> 00:20:13,844
You are the most cold, intractable, unapproachable, distant,

354
00:20:13,845 --> 00:20:16,356
stubborn, cold man I've ever known!

355
00:20:16,357 --> 00:20:18,077
You said "cold" twice, Mr. Egghead.

356
00:20:18,078 --> 00:20:19,250
Egghead? Egghead?

357
00:20:19,251 --> 00:20:20,704
You said "egghead" twice, too.

358
00:20:20,705 --> 00:20:22,437
Oh, you are so infuriating!

359
00:20:22,438 --> 00:20:23,935
Oh, you're no day at the beach either.

360
00:20:23,936 --> 00:20:24,972
You know what you are?

361
00:20:24,973 --> 00:20:27,347
I'll tell you later, it's time for my program.

362
00:20:33,342 --> 00:20:36,416
Dad, I don't think you see how serious this is.

363
00:20:36,417 --> 00:20:37,921
Oh, will you give it a rest?

364
00:20:38,052 --> 00:20:40,724
Look. We're not getting alone, and it's not getting any better.

365
00:20:43,349 --> 00:20:46,167
I'm not sure how to say this, but ah...

366
00:20:46,976 --> 00:20:51,604
I ah, I'm afraid I'm gonna have to...

367
00:20:51,986 --> 00:20:53,574
I know what you're trying to say.

368
00:20:53,575 --> 00:20:55,639
"You want what's best for both of us."

369
00:20:55,640 --> 00:20:58,704
You want to get me out of here, then you can have your own space,

370
00:20:58,705 --> 00:21:01,997
and I'll have my own space, and we can put an end to all this bickering.

371
00:21:03,284 --> 00:21:04,291
Well, yes.

372
00:21:05,665 --> 00:21:07,272
I guess it wasn't so hard to say after all.

373
00:21:07,273 --> 00:21:09,836
Except for one thing. I'm not going.

374
00:21:10,049 --> 00:21:11,082
What?

375
00:21:11,083 --> 00:21:14,002
Look, you want us to forge some great father-son relationship,

376
00:21:14,003 --> 00:21:15,390
to make some connection.

377
00:21:15,391 --> 00:21:19,149
Well, that kind of thing takes a couple of years, not a couple of days, doesn't it?

378
00:21:19,150 --> 00:21:20,613
You're the shrink.

379
00:21:22,255 --> 00:21:23,750
Couple of years, huh?

380
00:21:23,751 --> 00:21:25,634
Ah, it'll go by before you know it.

381
00:21:26,861 --> 00:21:29,340
Either that, or it'll seem like eternity.

382
00:21:36,679 --> 00:21:38,651
I'm willing to give it a shot if you are.

383
00:21:41,178 --> 00:21:42,374
Okay

384
00:21:42,556 --> 00:21:45,412
Great. How about you and me having a beer together?

385
00:21:46,150 --> 00:21:50,531
Wow. You know, in all these years you've never asked me that.

386
00:21:51,568 --> 00:21:52,975
I'd love to have a beer with you, dad.

387
00:21:52,976 --> 00:21:56,002
Well then, you better haul ass, 'cause the store closes in ten minutes.

388
00:21:56,003 --> 00:21:57,187
Right.

